<graph edgedefault="undirected"><node id="ACC">
  <data key="d0">ACC</data>
  <data key="d1">organization</data>
  <data key="d2">ACC is a professional industrial organization that operates several manufacturing facilities across various locations, including Archbold, York, Chattanooga, Troy, Albion, and Belvidere. The company primarily produces foundry casting products and manages internal coal grinding requirements to support its industrial operations. Beyond its physical manufacturing presence, the name ACC—sometimes referred to in records as "Archbold" or "Minerals"—is also used to identify a specific software component involved in post-billing smoke test comparisons and serves as a recurring identifier for evidentiary records within legal transcript indices. 

The organization manages its procurement and supply chain through an Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) system, which tracks inventory, weight measurements, deliveries, and payments. ACC’s procurement strategy involves a combination of formal purchase orders, such as PO-11, PO-12, and POs 17 through 21, and informal communications regarding material requirements. Key individuals associated with the company’s operations and legal matters include Dwayne Cotton, Neil Miller, and Rachel Perkins, as well as former employees Mike Wagner and Tom Reed. During legal proceedings, the company has been represented by Mr. Wentz and other legal designees.

For over a decade, ACC maintained an amicable business relationship with Fire Star Energy Resources LLC, acting as a primary customer for coal supplies. Under a two-year contract, ACC typically ordered between 10,000 and 12,000 tons of coal annually at a fixed delivered price, sourced from mines such as the Lipari and B&amp;W facilities. This relationship became strained in March 2022 due to disputes over coal requirements, high sulfur content in delivered materials, and fuel surcharges imposed by Fire Star. Additionally, Fire Star alleged that ACC failed to make timely payments, leading to a cessation of deliveries in June 2022.

In response to the halted supply, ACC initiated a lawsuit and filed a legal complaint against Fire Star for contract violations. The litigation involves specific disagreements over how coal requirements were calculated for the Archbold plant and claims regarding coal intended for the Troy facility. Throughout the dispute, Fire Star demanded payment assurances, while ACC alleged it was a victim of tactical payment processing delays. Despite the ongoing legal case, which has involved the production of various exhibits and discovery requests, ACC has participated in settlement negotiations and expressed a willingness to provide financial assurances to resolve the conflict.</data>
