<node id="Cotton">
  <data key="d0">Cotton</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Cotton refers to two distinct entities identified within the provided descriptions: an individual involved in industrial coal logistics and a material commodity that is a subject of legal proceedings.

In the first context, Cotton is an individual who plays a multifaceted role in the coal supply chain and transportation operations associated with Fire Star. Described as a "right-hand man" and close associate of an individual named Dwayne, Cotton serves as a loader operator and a truck owner, utilizing his own vehicle to conduct deliveries. Within the organizational hierarchy, Cotton serves as a key communication link; he has been designated as a primary contact for ordering coal and a secondary contact for delivery instructions when Dwayne is unavailable. His involvement in these operations includes receiving reports of supply shortages via text message and attempting to facilitate a "spot buy" of coal for the Belvidere plant. 

Furthermore, Cotton's activities have been the subject of scrutiny in legal contexts. He was reportedly involved in an unauthorized plan to move coal from Fire Star. In another instance, although he was contacted to coordinate a direct coal transportation arrangement, he ultimately declined the proposal. 

In the second context, Cotton refers to a physical material or commodity. In this capacity, it serves as a central subject of discussion and contract within legal proceedings, representing the textile fiber or crop rather than a person. This entity is the foundational element of specific legal disputes or agreements mentioned in the case documentation.&lt;SEP&gt;Cotton is the witness providing testimony during a legal deposition concerning business communications and coal procurement records.&lt;SEP&gt;Cotton is an individual whom the witness assumes is represented by the initial 'C' at the top of a text message series.&lt;SEP&gt;Cotton is a material or commodity that is frequently referenced and indexed as a subject within the legal transcript.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3e53329a256cc082bedeaabb7ee866bb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3aa6b92318a7dbc503df2e6bc0457f59&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b14692172e18d355177e1f52adca6616&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-72864d43546b0fdb0889bb6341c0c099&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-20985475deeff0feffae4d18b011ee8e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ea56e06fa48990cb993a7e9f44e99a73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-254a838d380639a750a841f49783616f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f84d5551c37eb2124ad1961273595bcd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-639c2a2ef1907dfbc4a114c9f1c48240&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3768689425a6da71a09b43a110e4c9b3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c2dc9b5b950d7e245002aa75cb40b381</data>
  <data key="d4">Deposition by Defendant -- Neil Miller (Manager at Plaintiff) -- April 14, 2023, 1316.pdf&lt;SEP&gt;Deposition by Plaintiff -- Timothy Jones (Owner of Defendant) -- July 17, 2023, 0938.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1777299028</data>
