<node id="Fire Star">
  <data key="d0">Fire Star</data>
  <data key="d1">organization</data>
  <data key="d2">Fire Star, also referred to as Steyer or FireStar Energy, is a professional coal supply and logistics organization established around 2015. The company serves as a primary provider of raw and ground coal to several industrial facilities, functioning as both a broker and a production entity. Management of the firm is led by an individual known as "The Witness," who oversees 90 percent of operations, while financial matters are managed by Tim. Other key personnel associated with the organization include Barry Hunter, Dwayne Jones (also referred to as Duane Jones), and Dwayne Couch.

The organization manages the sourcing, processing, and delivery of coal, maintaining relationships with contract miners and entities such as B&amp;W Resources, Inc. to procure materials from sites like the Chavies mine. Fire Star operates its own loadout facilities, which include two sides known as London and Manchester; the company notably expanded its footprint by purchasing the Manchester facility in 2022. To meet industrial requirements, the company’s coal products are expected to adhere to specific quality standards, including a 13,000 BTU thermal value and a maximum one percent sulfur content. Logistics are handled centrally, with the company coordinating weekly tonnage requirements—often involving 400 to 800 tons—and issuing invoices based on precise weight confirmations.

Fire Star maintained long-term business relationships with several major customers, most notably Lipari and the American Colloid Company (ACC). The company was responsible for coal deliveries to several industrial accounts, specifically providing products to plants in Archbold, Albion, Belvidere, and Chattanooga. For several years, Fire Star held a right of first refusal on certain business opportunities and managed regular purchase orders and shipments for ACC. However, its relationship with ACC, which began prior to January 2016, began to experience significant friction between March 2021 and March 2022.

The decline of the partnership was marked by operational and financial disputes, including allegations of volume shortages, quality issues, and a lack of logistical transparency. Financial tensions intensified when Fire Star implemented fuel surcharges and demanded payment assurances, such as a letter of credit, in response to a history of late payments from ACC. These conflicts eventually resulted in a legal case involving allegations of breach of contract and non-delivery of materials. The dispute reached a peak in June 2022 when Fire Star ceased shipments, forcing ACC to find alternative sources. Following the discovery of company records and legal proceedings, the combination of performance failures and litigation led to settlement negotiations and the reported shutdown of the Fire Star facility.</data>
