</node>
<node id="Annual Coal Volume">
  <data key="d0">Annual Coal Volume</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">The Annual Coal Volume represents the total quantity of coal delivered per year, which the Deponent identifies as being consistently over 15,000 tons.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3aa6b92318a7dbc503df2e6bc0457f59</data>
  <data key="d4">Deposition by Defendant -- Neil Miller (Manager at Plaintiff) -- April 14, 2023, 1316.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1777295573</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Coal">
  <data key="d0">Coal</data>
  <data key="d1">naturalobject</data>
  <data key="d2">Coal is a primary industrial raw material and natural resource that serves as a central commodity in various manufacturing, energy, and heating sectors. Beyond its traditional use as a fuel for power plants, it is a critical ingredient in the production of molds and foundry casting products. In specific industrial contexts, coal is frequently ground and pulverized into a fine powder—a process notable at the Archbold plant—to support manufacturing facilities in locations such as Belvidere and Chattanooga. The material is heavily managed to meet increased seasonal demand for heating and survival during the winter months.

The resource is characterized by specific quality metrics, including BTU values, sulfur levels, ash content, moisture, and physical dimensions, such as "two-by-one" sizing. Coal exists in various forms throughout the supply chain, ranging from unprocessed "cover" and chunk coal to processed stoker and ground powder. To remain viable for industrial use, the resource must meet strict technical specifications that vary by plant. Consequently, coal is subject to rigorous sampling and testing to ensure it meets necessary standards and to resolve discrepancies in quality grades.

Logistically, coal is sourced from strip jobs and specific sites, including the Lipari, B&amp;W, and Chavies mines, as well as mines located near Hazard. The supply chain often involves contract miners and brokerage by entities such as Fire Star Energy Resources LLC. The material is processed at tipple and load-out facilities before being transported via barge, train, or truck. Certain facilities, like the Archbold plant, rely exclusively on truck deliveries, typically receiving five to six loads per week. Inventory is measured in tons and tracked through Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) systems to maintain adequate stockpiles.

Coal has been the focal point of significant business and legal disputes, particularly between suppliers like Fire Star Energy and customers such as ACC. These disputes, spanning 2021 through 2023, have centered on procurement logistics, contract obligations, price volatility, and delivery shortages driven by high market demand or mechanical breakdowns. A notable quality dispute occurred in March 2021 regarding concerns over high sulfur levels, which led to supply delays and extensive legal testimony. Throughout these proceedings, coal remains the primary resource discussed in relation to shipment logistics, purchase orders, and production requirements.</data>
