<node id="Mr. Hunter">
  <data key="d0">Mr. Hunter</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Mr. Hunter is a legal professional and attorney who serves as a key participant in judicial proceedings, most notably within Case: 3:22-cv-01342-JZ. In this context, he plays a central role in the discovery process, specifically during depositions, where he acts as a primary examiner responsible for eliciting witness testimony to ensure accurate documentation within the legal transcript. He conducts formal direct, cross, and recross-examinations of individuals such as Aric Wentz and Neil Miller. His questioning often delves into intricate business and operational details, including plant storage, inventory records, data entries, and formal business communications. His inquiries also explore broader business practices such as contract negotiations, purchase orders, coal purchases, and financial credits, particularly as they relate to the requirements of entities like ACC.

In addition to his role as an examiner, Mr. Hunter serves as legal counsel representing witnesses during deposition proceedings. In this capacity, he actively protects his clients' interests by objecting to the form of questions and specific lines of inquiry, such as those regarding a witness’s external business interests. He frequently intervenes to provide instructions to the witness and to clarify the scope of inquiries—specifically regarding mines, geographical locations such as Hazard, and the identities of individuals including Duane Jones and Pat Hauser. Furthermore, he provides reminders to witnesses during their testimony, clarifies legal terms, and interjects to establish accurate timelines of events.

Throughout the legal process, Mr. Hunter is responsible for the identification and introduction of legal exhibits, including Exhibit 14, and the management of related legal correspondence and missing invoices. While utilizing digital tools like Exhibit Share, he has expressed technical difficulties in viewing digital documents and has addressed technical audio issues during the proceedings. He also manages the logistical aspects of the depositions, including requesting breaks, discussing scheduling, and indicating when he has no further questions for a witness. His professional interactions include communicating with other participants, such as Ms. Rathke, whom he refers to as Sarah; during these interactions, he has been known to comment on the use of technology and dispute matters related to scheduling, break times, and the level of professionalism maintained during the proceedings.</data>
