<node id="Archbold Plant">
  <data key="d0">Archbold Plant</data>
  <data key="d1">location</data>
  <data key="d2">The Archbold Plant is an industrial manufacturing and processing facility located in Archbold, Ohio, approximately one hour west of Toledo. Owned and operated by ACC, the facility specializes in the production of foundry casting products and other specific goods. It serves as a vital component of the organization’s logistics chain, functioning not only as a primary production site but also as a "gap filler" within the ACC system. In this capacity, the plant provides essential materials and support to other facilities when production issues or supply shortages arise elsewhere in the network.

A core function of the Archbold Plant is the processing and grinding of coal. The facility receives raw coal shipments—historically supplied by Fire Star Energy Resources LLC (also known as Fire Star)—and grinds the material into a work-in-progress ingredient. This ground coal is utilized for the plant's own manufacturing needs and is distributed to satisfy the operational requirements of other locations within the system, specifically the Belvidere, Troy, and Albion plants. The facility is notably responsible for performing dedicated grinding work for the Albion plant and serves as the central hub where ACC's coal needs and deliveries are managed.

To support these intensive operations, the Archbold Plant maintains a high demand for coal, with an annual requirement of 15,000 to 20,000 tons and an on-site storage capacity of approximately 1,000 tons. In addition to its physical manufacturing roles, the facility is responsible for various administrative and logistical tasks, including the recording of coal deliveries and the handling of invoice approvals. Operational records indicate that coal requirements and deliveries were meticulously tracked through May 2022, with specific operational context noted as early as July 2021.

Despite its importance, the Archbold Plant has encountered several operational challenges and constraints. The facility has faced quality issues with received coal that required resolution and instances where deliveries were recorded under mistaken classifications. There have also been reported delays in payments associated with this specific point in the logistics chain. Furthermore, the plant has occasionally reached its processing and storage limits, rendering it unable to handle certain shipments due to capacity constraints and the use of lower-quality cover coal. Regardless of these challenges, the Archbold Plant remains a primary site for coal delivery, processing, and distribution within its industrial network.</data>
