<node id="Chattanooga">
  <data key="d0">Chattanooga</data>
  <data key="d1">location</data>
  <data key="d2">Chattanooga is a city and industrial location that figures prominently in legal proceedings, particularly concerning business activities and contractual disputes. It is the site of an industrial plant operated by ACC, which is identified as a facility that utilizes coal. Additionally, the company Fire Star is noted for having previously supplied a plant in Chattanooga for a specific duration of time.

The city is central to a series of business transactions involving coal shipments and specific invoices dating back to mid-2021. These transactions, which included detailed delivery tracking, became a point of contention due to unpaid invoices that ultimately caused a rift between the involved parties. Chattanooga is explicitly linked to a particular contract discussed during the legal proceedings, highlighting its role as a key geographic point for the events under review.

Throughout the legal documentation and case transcripts, Chattanooga is referenced multiple times, appearing in keyword indices and specifically on page 28 of the transcript index. The records also account for the location through at least one instance of a variant spelling, further cementing its relevance as a recurring geographic reference in the context of the case's evidence and testimony.&lt;SEP&gt;Chattanooga is a city in Tennessee where a coal-receiving plant is located.&lt;SEP&gt;A business location referred to as "the Chat" in communications regarding rebidding and business opportunities.&lt;SEP&gt;Chattanooga is a city referenced in the transcript index, noted in connection with chat discussions.</data>
