<edge source="Belvidere" target="Fire Star">
  <data key="d7">4.0</data>
  <data key="d8">Coal from Fire Star was delivered to the Belvidere plant, totaling approximately 271 tons according to testimony.&lt;SEP&gt;Fire Star provided coal that was delivered to Belvidere, allegedly without Fire Star's knowledge of the destination.&lt;SEP&gt;Fire Star provides the coal that eventually supplies Belvidere, though Fire Star is allegedly unaware of the final destination.&lt;SEP&gt;Fire Star supplied coal by shipping it directly to the Belvidere plant.</data>
  <data key="d9">commercial activity,delivery,direct shipment,indirect supply,supply,supply chain</data>
  <data key="d10">chunk-3e53329a256cc082bedeaabb7ee866bb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b14692172e18d355177e1f52adca6616&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-239b957363afa06896c850b0b3096cab&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-76b142c69bd1fd0042f02d144521dea3</data>
  <data key="d11">Deposition by Defendant -- Neil Miller (Manager at Plaintiff) -- April 14, 2023, 1316.pdf&lt;SEP&gt;Deposition by Defendant -- Aric Wentz (Supervisor at Plaintiff) -- April 14, 2023, 0859.pdf</data>
  <data key="d12">1777297064</data>
  <data key="d13"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="Belvidere" target="Coal">
  <data key="d7">6.0</data>
  <data key="d8">The Belvidere plant uses coal as a necessary raw material for its manufacturing processes.&lt;SEP&gt;Coal production records include shipments delivered to Belvidere.&lt;SEP&gt;The Belvidere plant had an urgent operational need for coal supply.&lt;SEP&gt;Coal is delivered via trucks to the Belvidere plant location.&lt;SEP&gt;Belvidere is a specific location where coal status is monitored and reported.&lt;SEP&gt;The transcript index links Belvidere and coal together in its header section.</data>
  <data key="d9">delivery,distribution,geographic association,industrial usage,inventory management,logistics,raw material,resource demand,shipment,subject matter,utility</data>
  <data key="d10">chunk-3e53329a256cc082bedeaabb7ee866bb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cbd2c15dff71dc080694d39bcb9aee57&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3d6d709d0ec6b3472961b88797a09fc4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cf5bccaff8fd537a70e39101e74dafe1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5ff8ea4fb9a276eb3036f6b13650d835&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2b265eecbe7a5b0e28f5a49767bab851</data>
  <data key="d11">Deposition by Defendant -- Neil Miller (Manager at Plaintiff) -- April 14, 2023, 1316.pdf&lt;SEP&gt;Deposition by Defendant -- Aric Wentz (Supervisor at Plaintiff) -- April 14, 2023, 0859.pdf&lt;SEP&gt;Deposition by Plaintiff -- Dwayne Jones (Owner of Defendant) -- August 17, 2023, 1101.pdf</data>
  <data key="d12">1777297177</data>
  <data key="d13"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="Belvidere" target="Archbold">
  <data key="d7">10.0</data>
  <data key="d8">The relationship between Archbold and Belvidere is primarily characterized by Archbold's role in managing and supplying the coal requirements for the Belvidere facility. As part of this arrangement, Archbold oversees the coverage and operational needs of the Belvidere plant, serving as a central hub in its supply chain. The logistical process typically involves coal being transported to the Archbold facility, where it is unloaded and reloaded before being moved to Belvidere. There have been ongoing discussions regarding these logistics, specifically concerning whether coal deliveries are consistently routed through Archbold before arriving at the Belvidere plant.

In addition to supply management, Archbold provides specialized operational support and services to the Belvidere facility. This includes performing coal grinding services on an irregular, as-needed basis. Archbold has also provided technical assistance to Belvidere, notably supporting the plant during its combustible dust project. 

The partnership has faced certain operational challenges and dependencies. There are records of Archbold failing to provide the necessary coal to Belvidere due to quality issues encountered during the processing stage at the Archbold plant. Despite these occasional disruptions, Archbold remains a key entity in managing the material requirements and processing needs essential to Belvidere’s operations.</data>
