<edge source="Fire Star" target="Coal">
  <data key="d7">36.0</data>
  <data key="d8">The relationship between Coal and Fire Star is defined by Fire Star’s comprehensive role as the primary supplier, processor, and logistics coordinator for coal sourced from a strip job and processing plant. Operating as a direct supplier rather than a broker, Fire Star was responsible for mining, sourcing, and building inventory to meet the specific needs of its clients. The entity established the technical specifications for the material, ensuring that the coal met agreed-upon standards for use in industrial manufacturing. Its business activities encompassed the entire supply chain, including the trade, hauling, and direct shipment of coal to fulfill various purchase orders.

In terms of operational logistics, Fire Star managed the transportation and delivery of coal to multiple industrial locations, most notably providing regular weekly loads to the ACC Archbold plant. Fire Star’s management understood that their supply was intended to service the needs of several plants within the customer’s organization. While Fire Star shipped specific types of coal throughout 2020 and 2021, the entity delivered a total volume of approximately 10,000 to 11,000 tons in 2021 alone.

The business arrangement eventually faced significant strain due to a combination of supply chain failures and financial disputes. Beginning in March 2021, Fire Star failed to meet required delivery volumes, leading to substantial shortfalls. Furthermore, the entity began withholding shipments, citing unpaid invoices as the reason for the disruption. These delivery failures, coupled with mounting concerns over material quality, resulted in legal testimony regarding Fire Star's role and its subsequent inability to fulfill contractual obligations. Following a series of complaints—during which the coal was identified as the same material later used by Neil Miller’s company—Fire Star was eventually shut down, marking the end of its involvement in the coal supply market.</data>
