<edge source="Mr. Hunter" target="Ms. Rathke">
  <data key="d7">42.0</data>
  <data key="d8">The relationship between Mr. Hunter and Ms. Rathke is defined by their roles as opposing legal representatives participating in a formal deposition and witness examination. As legal professionals, they interact within a structured adversarial environment where they take turns as the questioning attorney and the opposing counsel responsible for monitoring testimony. Their relationship is characterized by a mix of procedural challenges, legal debates, and the collaborative management of the deposition's logistical requirements.

During the proceedings, Mr. Hunter and Ms. Rathke frequently engage in legal disputes regarding the examination of witnesses. Ms. Rathke regularly interposes objections to the form, foundation, structure, and phrasing of Mr. Hunter’s questions, particularly concerning factual predicates and calculations. She also provides instructions to deponents to protect the integrity of the record and debates the relevance of specific inquiries into a witness's business interests. Conversely, Mr. Hunter interjects during Ms. Rathke’s lines of questioning to object to the form and nature of her inquiries, ensure witnesses are focused on correct dates, and, in some instances, terminate specific lines of inquiry. Despite these adversarial exchanges, both parties acknowledge clarifications provided by the other to maintain the progress of the testimony.

In addition to their courtroom-style maneuvers, Mr. Hunter and Ms. Rathke coordinate on the administrative and technical aspects of the deposition. They interact to clarify details concerning legal exhibits, such as the dates associated with Exhibit 8, and discuss the production of evidence. Their communications also cover scheduling and logistics, including professional disagreements regarding the timing of lunch breaks. Furthermore, the two collaborate to resolve technical issues, such as problems with the audio feed. Their professional dynamic includes moments of courtesy, such as when Mr. Hunter expressed that he was impressed by Ms. Rathke's use of technology during the proceeding.</data>
  <data key="d9">adversarial interaction,advocacy,clarification,conflict,deposition,dialogue,examination,interaction,legal dispute,legal interaction,legal objection,legal procedure,legal proceeding,legal proceedings,objection,procedural conflict,procedural interaction,professional dispute,professional interaction,professional presence,scheduling conflict,social interaction</data>
